[{"sha":"227a65a8f04c92a0c63425dd383cb0b5e8917bd0","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Add Lane labels to scheduling profiler marks

This changes profiler marks from a format like "--schedule-render-1" like "--schedule-render-1-Sync" which will enable the profiler itself to show more meaningful labels for updates and render work.

There are a couple of downsides to this proposed change:
1. It reqiures maintaining a map of bitmask range to string/label in ReactFiberLanel. Hopefully not a huge burden but something we would need to remember to keep in sync.
2. It increases the size of User Timing data logged by the profiler during render. (I don't think there's a way around this since there's no initialization event where we can log a standalone mapping). [{"sha":"ba45035f3a69de4e0bfe6b5a5705c486940634af","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Fix replay issue in round-robin reads.

Previously we indexed requests by (1) round index and (2) pointer addresses. This is a problem when we get multiple requests for the same round, e.g. due to retries. This could cause the same consumer to be counted multiple times, potentially producing a round of data before all consumers are ready.

Change-Id: Iff329b8f81777f895333726e8ca98e2d3ad4ddb5","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/testkevinbonz/tensorflow/commits/443f13e41a34d70dc5dd9509e700ccf79324b5a2"},{"sha":"750beea911c7b82b45667d62021cb0bbf22709c8","author":{"name":"Sanjoy Das","email":"d72748a98fd8b476107003df407128e166d060ac@google.com"},"message":"Set the default value for the use_gpu-param to True in test utilities

Also, fix a bug in IsFunctionCallOp found by this CL.

Contrary to what it sounds like, `use_gpu` does not force the test to run on
GPUs, it merely *allows* the test to run on GPUs (there is a separate
`force_gpu` option for forcing).  This means setting `use_gpu` to `True` means
that the test will run on GPUs if one is available.

Given that setting `use_gpu` to `True` by default makes sense, and there should
be a good reason for a test to set it to `False` (which disallows GPU use, even
when one is available).

For this reason, this CL changes the default value of `use_gpu`.  As you can
see, this has already found a few real bugs.

In a later CL I will remove instances that pass use_gpu=True explicitly as those
should no longer be necessary.

[{"sha":"696e736be11b22e8d4fa40438d235b63db7fddde","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Warn if static flag is accidentally cleared (#20807)

* Warn if static flag is accidentally cleared

"Static" fiber flags are flags that are meant to exist for the lifetime
of a component. It's really important not to accidentally reset these,
because we use them to decide whether or not to perform some operation
on a tree (which we can do because they get bubbled via `subtreeFlags)`.

We've had several bugs that were caused by this mistake, so we actually
don't rely on static flags anywhere, yet. But we'd like to.

So let's roll out this warning and see if it fires anywhere. Once we
can confirm that there are no warnings, we can assume that it's safe
to start using static flags.

I did not wrap it behind a feature flag, because it's dev-only, and we
can use our internal warning filter to hide this from the console.

* Intentionally clear static flag to test warning

* Land enableTransitionEntanglement changes

Leaving the flag though because I plan to reuse it for additional,
similar changes.

* Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions

Currently we always assign the same lane to all transitions. This means
if there are two pending transitions at the same time, neither
transition can finish until both can finish, even if they affect
completely separate parts of the UI.

The new approach is to assign a different lane to each consecutive
transition, by shifting the bit to the right each time. When we reach
the end of the bit range, we cycle back to the first bit. In practice,
this should mean that all transitions get their own dedicated lane,
unless we have more pending transitions than lanes, which should
be rare.

We retain our existing behavior of assigning the same lane to all
transitions within the same event. This is achieved by caching the first
lane assigned to a transition, then re-using that one until the next
React task, by which point the event must have finished. This preserves
the guarantee that all transition updates that result from a single
event will be consistent.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62"},{"sha":"b4658f2daa4990ef8057335cd7202b479bd8d41a","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@gmail.com"},"message":"Reduce some constant duplication (#20761)

Now that interleaved updates are added to a special queue, we no longer
need to shift them into their own lane. We can add to a lane that's
already in the middle of rendering without risk of tearing.

See #20615 for more background.

I've only changed this in the new fork, and only behind the
enableTransitionEntanglements flag.

Most of this commit involves updating tests. The "shift-to-a-new" lane
trick was intentionally used in a handful of tests where two or more
updates need to be scheduled in different lanes. Most of these tests
were written before `startTransition` existed, and all of them were
written before transitions were assigned arbitrary lanes.

So I ported these tests to use `startTransition` instead, which is the

Change-Id: Iff329b8f81777f895333726e8ca98e2d3ad4ddb5","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/KabirKwatra/tensorflow/commits/443f13e41a34d70dc5dd9509e700ccf79324b5a2"},{"sha":"750beea911c7b82b45667d62021cb0bbf22709c8","author":{"name":"Sanjoy Das","email":"d72748a98fd8b476107003df407128e166d060ac@google.com"},"message":"Set the default value for the use_gpu-param to True in test utilities

Also, fix a bug in IsFunctionCallOp found by this CL.

Contrary to what it sounds like, `use_gpu` does not force the test to run on
GPUs, it merely *allows* the test to run on GPUs (there is a separate
`force_gpu` option for forcing).  This means setting `use_gpu` to `True` means
that the test will run on GPUs if one is available.

Given that setting `use_gpu` to `True` by default makes sense, and there should
be a good reason for a test to set it to `False` (which disallows GPU use, even
when one is available).

For this reason, this CL changes the default value of `use_gpu`.  As you can
see, this has already found a few real bugs.

In a later CL I will remove instances that pass use_gpu=True explicitly as those
should no longer be necessary.

[{"sha":"4cd21680a52cf489c6cf707f7f98225a3f7bcc78","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Skip MLIR TPU Bridge if the graph does not have any TPU ops or no TPU devices in device set.

We run into cases where none of the ops in the graph have `_tpu_replicate` attribute, or the device set does not have TPU devices. In such cases, the MLIR TPU bridge passes sometimes still modify the graph, for example, constant folding or resource op decomposition. So, the round trip is not idempotent on such graphs.

[{"sha":"05756fcc81f6b5c2152d597b6285b350e7b05e36","author":{"name":"Doe Hyun Yoon","email":"2bed64b9009034c7d8617d2ea58929f25c2cde7d@google.com"},"message":"Set default device info if device type is neither CPU nor GPU.

OpLevelCostEstimator::GetDeviceInfo() returns GFLOPs/sec and GB/sec of
the assumed machine, but currently it assumes the device type is either CPU
or GPU. We didn't expect other device types would be passed during the Grappler
optimization as transfer operations such as _Send and _Recv are added when
a graph actually runs. In some occasions, we encountered the input graph
includes _HostSend op (it is possible that the graph includes _Send or _Recv
ops; that happened in some test cases).

Device type not CPU / GPU currently causes crash; to avoid such a case, we
assume unknown device type as transfer operations over PCIe; setting
default PCIe x16 gen3 bandwidth to avoid crash.

As the GetDeviceInfo() method is virtual, one may override this method
if more precise device info is needed.

Currently Tensor does not have a constructor that allows to pass TensorBuffer ownership to Tensor. It can only be done with Ref()/Unref() operations pair.

Although it would be nice to have "take ownership" constructor with a simple pointer argument, it is harder to signal this intention in a type signature.

Currently Tensor does not have a constructor that allows to pass TensorBuffer ownership to Tensor. It can only be done with Ref()/Unref() operations pair.

core::RefCountPtr<TensorBuffer> clearly communicates the ownership of the buffer.

Although it would be nice to have "take ownership" constructor with a simple pointer argument, it is harder to signal this intention in a type signature.

Change-Id: I28966d39de769c7388a0ef300d2006c070b20c14","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/d73cfcdbba5473a6468523aeb2b89c84f738a230"},{"sha":"6d7e583c890e852319629ee00bf8ca87c233475b","author":{"name":"Jose Baiocchi","email":"2c5064b37befcda621d52370dff81833faf858cd@google.com"},"message":"Allow locking the profiler via environment variable

Alternative to https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46544

Use case: Allow an outer profiler (e.g., a command-line tool) to set an environment variable to prevent interference from TF Profiler. We already have mutual exclusion of profiler clients via ProfilerLock to guarantee at most one profiler client can actually profile. The environment variable TF_DISABLE_PROFILING, when set to 1, disables all profiler clients. We assume that clients already know how to gracefully handle failure to profile.

A passive effect's cleanup function may throw after an unmount. Prior to this commit, such an error would be ignored. (React would not notify any error boundaries.) After this commit, React's behavior varies depending on which reconciler fork is being used.

For the old reconciler, React will call componentDidCatch for the nearest unmounted error boundary (if there is one). If there are no unmounted error boundaries, React will still swallow the error because the return pointer has been disconnected, so the normal error handling logic does not know how to traverse the tree to find the nearest still-mounted ancestor.

For the new reconciler, React will skip any unmounted boundaries and look for a still-mounted boundary. If one is found, it will call getDerivedStateFromError and/or componentDidCatch (depending on the type of boundary).

Tests have been added for both reconciler variants for now.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/eps1lon/react/commits/ffb749c95e0361b3cfbbfc4e1a73bfa2fda0aa93"},{"sha":"49cd77d24a5244d159be14671654da63932ea9be","author":{"name":"Toru Kobayashi","email":"411531d9265de69abb99eda19baab99e84bb4678@gmail.com"},"message":"fix: leak strict mode with UMD builds (#19614)","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/eps1lon/react/commits/49cd77d24a5244d159be14671654da63932ea9be"},{"sha":"702fad4b1b48ac8f626ed3f35e8f86f5ea728084","author":{"name":"CY Lim","email":"c066ac50b14c1331c64660a40fdb3f0986792698@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"refactor fb.me redirect link to reactjs.org/link (#19598)

* Parallelize Flow in CI

We added more host configs recently, and we run all the checks in
sequence, so sometimes Flow ends up being the slowest CI job.

This splits the job across multiple processes.

* Fix environment variable typo

Change-Id: I28966d39de769c7388a0ef300d2006c070b20c14","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/d73cfcdbba5473a6468523aeb2b89c84f738a230"},{"sha":"6d7e583c890e852319629ee00bf8ca87c233475b","author":{"name":"Jose Baiocchi","email":"2c5064b37befcda621d52370dff81833faf858cd@google.com"},"message":"Allow locking the profiler via environment variable

Alternative to https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46544

Use case: Allow an outer profiler (e.g., a command-line tool) to set an environment variable to prevent interference from TF Profiler. We already have mutual exclusion of profiler clients via ProfilerLock to guarantee at most one profiler client can actually profile. The environment variable TF_DISABLE_PROFILING, when set to 1, disables all profiler clients. We assume that clients already know how to gracefully handle failure to profile.

Alternative to https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46544

Use case: Allow an outer profiler (e.g., a command-line tool) to set an environment variable to prevent interference from TF Profiler. We already have mutual exclusion of profiler clients via ProfilerLock to guarantee at most one profiler client can actually profile. The environment variable TF_DISABLE_PROFILING, when set to 1, disables all profiler clients. We assume that clients already know how to gracefully handle failure to profile.

Change-Id: Iff329b8f81777f895333726e8ca98e2d3ad4ddb5","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Cache-Cloud/tensorflow/commits/443f13e41a34d70dc5dd9509e700ccf79324b5a2"},{"sha":"750beea911c7b82b45667d62021cb0bbf22709c8","author":{"name":"Sanjoy Das","email":"d72748a98fd8b476107003df407128e166d060ac@google.com"},"message":"Set the default value for the use_gpu-param to True in test utilities

Also, fix a bug in IsFunctionCallOp found by this CL.

Contrary to what it sounds like, `use_gpu` does not force the test to run on
GPUs, it merely *allows* the test to run on GPUs (there is a separate
`force_gpu` option for forcing).  This means setting `use_gpu` to `True` means
that the test will run on GPUs if one is available.

Given that setting `use_gpu` to `True` by default makes sense, and there should
be a good reason for a test to set it to `False` (which disallows GPU use, even
when one is available).

For this reason, this CL changes the default value of `use_gpu`.  As you can
see, this has already found a few real bugs.

In a later CL I will remove instances that pass use_gpu=True explicitly as those
should no longer be necessary.

Also, the x86 test behavior has changed:
  * removed the unnecessary testing script for x86 with Make and bazel.
  * This change means that we no longer need a special skylark rule for tflite_micro_cc_test and can instead directly use cc_test.
  * All the logs from the test are now visible on the terminal (previously we would only see logs on errors, which can be annoying
    for debugging)

Tested that the following commands:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 XTENSA_CORE=F1_190305_swupgrade run_keyword_benchmark -j8
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile run_keyword_benchmark -j8
```
execute without any error.

The output is someting like:
```
InitializeKeywordRunner() took 39 ticks (0 ms)
KeywordRunNIerations(1) took 42 ticks (0 ms)
KeywordRunNIerations(10) took 187 ticks (0 ms)
```

Prior to this change, benchmarks would have to be run with
`make test_keyword_benchmark` which would give a confusing output:

```
InitializeKeywordRunner() took 85 ticks (0 ms)
KeywordRunNIerations(1) took 27 ticks (0 ms)
KeywordRunNIerations(10) took 276 ticks (0 ms)
make: *** [tensorflow/lite/micro/benchmarks/Makefile.inc:28: test_keyword_benchmark] Error 1
```

Fixes http://b/168123200

Change-Id: I1d0203d945bfe3c1905dd956ce0612172861d276","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Cache-Cloud/tensorflow/commits/1540d6a89e826bc660118d08a7850776c2ed781c"},{"sha":"4cd21680a52cf489c6cf707f7f98225a3f7bcc78","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Skip MLIR TPU Bridge if the graph does not have any TPU ops or no TPU devices in device set.

We run into cases where none of the ops in the graph have `_tpu_replicate` attribute, or the device set does not have TPU devices. In such cases, the MLIR TPU bridge passes sometimes still modify the graph, for example, constant folding or resource op decomposition. So, the round trip is not idempotent on such graphs.

Signed-off-by: J-jaeyoung <jjy600901@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/upenderadepu/moby/commits/19eda6b9a2991733a7e5b8fb0c435bf55846461f"},{"sha":"5cc1753f2c9a52dd7f943f874d96cbdbc81aa542","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Fix daemon panic when starting container with invalid device cgroup rule

This fixes a panic when an invalid "device cgroup rule" is passed, resulting
in an "index out of range".

This bug was introduced in the original implementation in 1756af6fafabd9197feb56c0324e49dd7d30b11f,
but was not reproducible when using the CLI, because the same commit also added
client-side validation on the flag before making an API request. The following
example, uses an invalid rule (`c *:*  rwm` - two spaces before the permissions);

```console
$ docker run --rm --network=host --device-cgroup-rule='c *:*  rwm' busybox
invalid argument "c *:*  rwm" for "--device-cgroup-rule" flag: invalid device cgroup format 'c *:*  rwm'
```

Doing the same, but using the API results in a daemon panic when starting the container;

Create a container with an invalid device cgroup rule:

```console
curl -v \
  --unix-socket /var/run/docker.sock \
  "http://localhost/v1.41/containers/create?name=foobar" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"Image":"busybox:latest", "HostConfig":{"DeviceCgroupRules": ["c *:*  rwm"]}}'
```

Start the container:

```console
curl -v \
  --unix-socket /var/run/docker.sock \
  -X POST \
  "http://localhost/v1.41/containers/foobar/start"
```

Observe the daemon logs:

```
2021-01-22 12:53:03.313806 I | http: panic serving @: runtime error: index out of range [0] with length 0
goroutine 571 [running]:
net/http.(*conn).serve.func1(0xc000cb2d20)
	/usr/local/go/src/net/http/server.go:1795 +0x13b
panic(0x2f32380, 0xc000aebfc0)
	/usr/local/go/src/runtime/panic.go:679 +0x1b6
github.com/docker/docker/oci.AppendDevicePermissionsFromCgroupRules(0xc000175c00, 0x8, 0x8, 0xc0000bd380, 0x1, 0x4, 0x0, 0x0, 0xc0000e69c0, 0x0, ...)
	/go/src/github.com/docker/docker/oci/oci.go:34 +0x64f
```

This patch:

- fixes the panic, allowing the daemon to return an error on container start
- adds a unit-test to validate various permutations
- adds a "todo" to verify the regular expression (and handling) of the "a" (all) value

We should also consider performing this validation when _creating_ the container,
so that an error is produced early.

resources have been cleaned up unless you actually remove the container.

This change allows callers of the wait API or the events API to know
that all runtime resources for the container are released (e.g. IP
addresses).

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/upenderadepu/moby/commits/66dffbec86dbea1b04180699106d5b8a73d5424b"},{"sha":"4b5aa28f2466308acab98fc35586723492347fc5","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Do not set DOCKER_TMP to be owned by remapped root

The remapped root does not need access to this dir.
Having this owned by the remapped root opens the host up to an
uprivileged user on the host being able to escalate privileges.

While it would not be normal for the remapped UID to be used outside of
the container context, it could happen.

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>
(cherry picked from commit bfedd2725971303efb7a2fe5d6990317b381622f)
Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/upenderadepu/moby/commits/4b5aa28f2466308acab98fc35586723492347fc5"},{"sha":"7f5e39bd4f92ce6fcf9946aa8ccea91815c321c2","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Use real root with 0701 perms

Various dirs in /var/lib/docker contain data that needs to be mounted
into a container. For this reason, these dirs are set to be owned by the
remapped root user, otherwise there can be permissions issues.
However, this uneccessarily exposes these dirs to an unprivileged user
on the host.

Instead, set the ownership of these dirs to the real root (or rather the
UID/GID of dockerd) with 0701 permissions, which allows the remapped
root to enter the directories but not read/write to them.
The remapped root needs to enter these dirs so the container's rootfs
can be configured... e.g. to mount /etc/resolve.conf.

This prevents an unprivileged user from having read/write access to
these dirs on the host.
The flip side of this is now any user can enter these directories.

While the field in the Go struct is named `NanoCPUs`, it has a JSON label to
use `NanoCpus`, which was added in the original pull request (not clear what
the reason was); 846baf1fd3efcbfbf9d3eb99e436ca9a59d3e185

Some notes:

- Golang processes field names case-insensitive, so when *using* the API,
  both cases should work, but when inspecting a container, the field is
  returned as `NanoCpus`.
- This only affects Containers.Resources. The `Limits` and `Reservation`
  for SwarmKit services and SwarmKit "nodes" do not override the name
  for JSON, so have the canonical (`NanoCPUs`) casing.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 356904310
Change-Id: Iff329b8f81777f895333726e8ca98e2d3ad4ddb5","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/NeatNerdPrime/tensorflow/commits/443f13e41a34d70dc5dd9509e700ccf79324b5a2"},{"sha":"750beea911c7b82b45667d62021cb0bbf22709c8","author":{"name":"Sanjoy Das","email":"d72748a98fd8b476107003df407128e166d060ac@google.com"},"message":"Set the default value for the use_gpu-param to True in test utilities

Also, fix a bug in IsFunctionCallOp found by this CL.

Contrary to what it sounds like, `use_gpu` does not force the test to run on
GPUs, it merely *allows* the test to run on GPUs (there is a separate
`force_gpu` option for forcing).  This means setting `use_gpu` to `True` means
that the test will run on GPUs if one is available.

Given that setting `use_gpu` to `True` by default makes sense, and there should
be a good reason for a test to set it to `False` (which disallows GPU use, even
when one is available).

For this reason, this CL changes the default value of `use_gpu`.  As you can
see, this has already found a few real bugs.

In a later CL I will remove instances that pass use_gpu=True explicitly as those
should no longer be necessary.

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/meunice/moby/commits/e192ce4009865ef96383f3162b40f58d52596790"},{"sha":"2bd46ed7e5a016f21b9259cec269340420fa7a63","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"api: fix NanoCPUs casing in swagger

While the field in the Go struct is named `NanoCPUs`, it has a JSON label to
use `NanoCpus`, which was added in the original pull request (not clear what
the reason was); 846baf1fd3efcbfbf9d3eb99e436ca9a59d3e185

Some notes:

- Golang processes field names case-insensitive, so when *using* the API,
  both cases should work, but when inspecting a container, the field is
  returned as `NanoCpus`.
- This only affects Containers.Resources. The `Limits` and `Reservation`

Change-Id: Iff329b8f81777f895333726e8ca98e2d3ad4ddb5","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/akram/tensorflow/commits/443f13e41a34d70dc5dd9509e700ccf79324b5a2"},{"sha":"750beea911c7b82b45667d62021cb0bbf22709c8","author":{"name":"Sanjoy Das","email":"d72748a98fd8b476107003df407128e166d060ac@google.com"},"message":"Set the default value for the use_gpu-param to True in test utilities

Also, fix a bug in IsFunctionCallOp found by this CL.

Contrary to what it sounds like, `use_gpu` does not force the test to run on
GPUs, it merely *allows* the test to run on GPUs (there is a separate
`force_gpu` option for forcing).  This means setting `use_gpu` to `True` means
that the test will run on GPUs if one is available.

Given that setting `use_gpu` to `True` by default makes sense, and there should
be a good reason for a test to set it to `False` (which disallows GPU use, even
when one is available).

For this reason, this CL changes the default value of `use_gpu`.  As you can
see, this has already found a few real bugs.

In a later CL I will remove instances that pass use_gpu=True explicitly as those
should no longer be necessary.

resources have been cleaned up unless you actually remove the container.

This change allows callers of the wait API or the events API to know

addresses).

While the field in the Go struct is named `NanoCPUs`, it has a JSON label to
use `NanoCpus`, which was added in the original pull request (not clear what
the reason was); 846baf1fd3efcbfbf9d3eb99e436ca9a59d3e185

Some notes:

- Golang processes field names case-insensitive, so when *using* the API,
  both cases should work, but when inspecting a container, the field is
  returned as `NanoCpus`.
- This only affects Containers.Resources. The `Limits` and `Reservation`
  for SwarmKit services and SwarmKit "nodes" do not override the name
  for JSON, so have the canonical (`NanoCPUs`) casing.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 356904310
Change-Id: Iff329b8f81777f895333726e8ca98e2d3ad4ddb5","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Nicholas282787728/tensorflow/commits/443f13e41a34d70dc5dd9509e700ccf79324b5a2"},{"sha":"750beea911c7b82b45667d62021cb0bbf22709c8","author":{"name":"Sanjoy Das","email":"d72748a98fd8b476107003df407128e166d060ac@google.com"},"message":"Set the default value for the use_gpu-param to True in test utilities

Also, fix a bug in IsFunctionCallOp found by this CL.

Contrary to what it sounds like, `use_gpu` does not force the test to run on
GPUs, it merely *allows* the test to run on GPUs (there is a separate
`force_gpu` option for forcing).  This means setting `use_gpu` to `True` means
that the test will run on GPUs if one is available.

Given that setting `use_gpu` to `True` by default makes sense, and there should
be a good reason for a test to set it to `False` (which disallows GPU use, even
when one is available).

For this reason, this CL changes the default value of `use_gpu`.  As you can
see, this has already found a few real bugs.

In a later CL I will remove instances that pass use_gpu=True explicitly as those
should no longer be necessary.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 356858844
Change-Id: I2511fabb769bb5211b4d7d9c4185df4f3ce0e4cc","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/akram/tensorflow/commits/ba45035f3a69de4e0bfe6b5a5705c486940634af"},{"sha":"05756fcc81f6b5c2152d597b6285b350e7b05e36","author":{"name":"Doe Hyun Yoon","email":"2bed64b9009034c7d8617d2ea58929f25c2cde7d@google.com"},"message":"Set default device info if device type is neither CPU nor GPU.

OpLevelCostEstimator::GetDeviceInfo() returns GFLOPs/sec and GB/sec of
the assumed machine, but currently it assumes the device type is either CPU
or GPU. We didn't expect other device types would be passed during the Grappler
optimization as transfer operations such as _Send and _Recv are added when
a graph actually runs. In some occasions, we encountered the input graph
includes _HostSend op (it is possible that the graph includes _Send or _Recv
ops; that happened in some test cases).

Device type not CPU / GPU currently causes crash; to avoid such a case, we
assume unknown device type as transfer operations over PCIe; setting
default PCIe x16 gen3 bandwidth to avoid crash.

As the GetDeviceInfo() method is virtual, one may override this method
if more precise device info is needed.

Change-Id: I28966d39de769c7388a0ef300d2006c070b20c14","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/testkevinbonz/tensorflow/commits/d73cfcdbba5473a6468523aeb2b89c84f738a230"},{"sha":"6d7e583c890e852319629ee00bf8ca87c233475b","author":{"name":"Jose Baiocchi","email":"2c5064b37befcda621d52370dff81833faf858cd@google.com"},"message":"Allow locking the profiler via environment variable

Alternative to https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46544

Use case: Allow an outer profiler (e.g., a command-line tool) to set an environment variable to prevent interference from TF Profiler. We already have mutual exclusion of profiler clients via ProfilerLock to guarantee at most one profiler client can actually profile. The environment variable TF_DISABLE_PROFILING, when set to 1, disables all profiler clients. We assume that clients already know how to gracefully handle failure to profile.

Currently Tensor does not have a constructor that allows to pass TensorBuffer ownership to Tensor. It can only be done with Ref()/Unref() operations pair.

core::RefCountPtr<TensorBuffer> clearly communicates the ownership of the buffer.

Although it would be nice to have "take ownership" constructor with a simple pointer argument, it is harder to signal this intention in a type signature.

Change-Id: I28966d39de769c7388a0ef300d2006c070b20c14","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Manas1820/tensorflow/commits/d73cfcdbba5473a6468523aeb2b89c84f738a230"},{"sha":"6d7e583c890e852319629ee00bf8ca87c233475b","author":{"name":"Jose Baiocchi","email":"2c5064b37befcda621d52370dff81833faf858cd@google.com"},"message":"Allow locking the profiler via environment variable

Alternative to https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46544

Use case: Allow an outer profiler (e.g., a command-line tool) to set an environment variable to prevent interference from TF Profiler. We already have mutual exclusion of profiler clients via ProfilerLock to guarantee at most one profiler client can actually profile. The environment variable TF_DISABLE_PROFILING, when set to 1, disables all profiler clients. We assume that clients already know how to gracefully handle failure to profile.

Currently Tensor does not have a constructor that allows to pass TensorBuffer ownership to Tensor. It can only be done with Ref()/Unref() operations pair.

core::RefCountPtr<TensorBuffer> clearly communicates the ownership of the buffer.

Although it would be nice to have "take ownership" constructor with a simple pointer argument, it is harder to signal this intention in a type signature.

Change-Id: I28966d39de769c7388a0ef300d2006c070b20c14","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/d73cfcdbba5473a6468523aeb2b89c84f738a230"},{"sha":"6d7e583c890e852319629ee00bf8ca87c233475b","author":{"name":"Jose Baiocchi","email":"2c5064b37befcda621d52370dff81833faf858cd@google.com"},"message":"Allow locking the profiler via environment variable

Alternative to https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46544

Use case: Allow an outer profiler (e.g., a command-line tool) to set an environment variable to prevent interference from TF Profiler. We already have mutual exclusion of profiler clients via ProfilerLock to guarantee at most one profiler client can actually profile. The environment variable TF_DISABLE_PROFILING, when set to 1, disables all profiler clients. We assume that clients already know how to gracefully handle failure to profile.

Previously we indexed requests by (1) round index and (2) pointer addresses. This is a problem when we get multiple requests for the same round, e.g. due to retries. This could cause the same consumer to be counted multiple times, potentially producing a round of data before all consumers are ready.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 356858844
Change-Id: I2511fabb769bb5211b4d7d9c4185df4f3ce0e4cc","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/ba45035f3a69de4e0bfe6b5a5705c486940634af"},{"sha":"05756fcc81f6b5c2152d597b6285b350e7b05e36","author":{"name":"Doe Hyun Yoon","email":"2bed64b9009034c7d8617d2ea58929f25c2cde7d@google.com"},"message":"Set default device info if device type is neither CPU nor GPU.

OpLevelCostEstimator::GetDeviceInfo() returns GFLOPs/sec and GB/sec of
the assumed machine, but currently it assumes the device type is either CPU
or GPU. We didn't expect other device types would be passed during the Grappler
optimization as transfer operations such as _Send and _Recv are added when
a graph actually runs. In some occasions, we encountered the input graph
includes _HostSend op (it is possible that the graph includes _Send or _Recv
ops; that happened in some test cases).

Device type not CPU / GPU currently causes crash; to avoid such a case, we
assume unknown device type as transfer operations over PCIe; setting
default PCIe x16 gen3 bandwidth to avoid crash.

As the GetDeviceInfo() method is virtual, one may override this method
if more precise device info is needed.

Currently Tensor does not have a constructor that allows to pass TensorBuffer ownership to Tensor. It can only be done with Ref()/Unref() operations pair.

core::RefCountPtr<TensorBuffer> clearly communicates the ownership of the buffer.

Although it would be nice to have "take ownership" constructor with a simple pointer argument, it is harder to signal this intention in a type signature.

Change-Id: I28966d39de769c7388a0ef300d2006c070b20c14","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/d73cfcdbba5473a6468523aeb2b89c84f738a230"},{"sha":"6d7e583c890e852319629ee00bf8ca87c233475b","author":{"name":"Jose Baiocchi","email":"2c5064b37befcda621d52370dff81833faf858cd@google.com"},"message":"Allow locking the profiler via environment variable

Alternative to https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46544

Use case: Allow an outer profiler (e.g., a command-line tool) to set an environment variable to prevent interference from TF Profiler. We already have mutual exclusion of profiler clients via ProfilerLock to guarantee at most one profiler client can actually profile. The environment variable TF_DISABLE_PROFILING, when set to 1, disables all profiler clients. We assume that clients already know how to gracefully handle failure to profile.

Currently Tensor does not have a constructor that allows to pass TensorBuffer ownership to Tensor. It can only be done with Ref()/Unref() operations pair.

core::RefCountPtr<TensorBuffer> clearly communicates the ownership of the buffer.

Although it would be nice to have "take ownership" constructor with a simple pointer argument, it is harder to signal this intention in a type signature.

Change-Id: I28966d39de769c7388a0ef300d2006c070b20c14","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/icpm/tensorflow/commits/d73cfcdbba5473a6468523aeb2b89c84f738a230"},{"sha":"6d7e583c890e852319629ee00bf8ca87c233475b","author":{"name":"Jose Baiocchi","email":"2c5064b37befcda621d52370dff81833faf858cd@google.com"},"message":"Allow locking the profiler via environment variable

Alternative to https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46544

Use case: Allow an outer profiler (e.g., a command-line tool) to set an environment variable to prevent interference from TF Profiler. We already have mutual exclusion of profiler clients via ProfilerLock to guarantee at most one profiler client can actually profile. The environment variable TF_DISABLE_PROFILING, when set to 1, disables all profiler clients. We assume that clients already know how to gracefully handle failure to profile.

  for JSON, so have the canonical (`NanoCPUs`) casing.

[{"sha":"05756fcc81f6b5c2152d597b6285b350e7b05e36","author":{"name":"Doe Hyun Yoon","email":"2bed64b9009034c7d8617d2ea58929f25c2cde7d@google.com"},"message":"Set default device info if device type is neither CPU nor GPU.

OpLevelCostEstimator::GetDeviceInfo() returns GFLOPs/sec and GB/sec of
the assumed machine, but currently it assumes the device type is either CPU
or GPU. We didn't expect other device types would be passed during the Grappler
optimization as transfer operations such as _Send and _Recv are added when
a graph actually runs. In some occasions, we encountered the input graph
includes _HostSend op (it is possible that the graph includes _Send or _Recv
ops; that happened in some test cases).

Device type not CPU / GPU currently causes crash; to avoid such a case, we
assume unknown device type as transfer operations over PCIe; setting
default PCIe x16 gen3 bandwidth to avoid crash.

As the GetDeviceInfo() method is virtual, one may override this method
if more precise device info is needed.

* Land enableTransitionEntanglement changes

Leaving the flag though because I plan to reuse it for additional,
similar changes.

* Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions

Currently we always assign the same lane to all transitions. This means
if there are two pending transitions at the same time, neither
transition can finish until both can finish, even if they affect
completely separate parts of the UI.

The new approach is to assign a different lane to each consecutive
transition, by shifting the bit to the right each time. When we reach
the end of the bit range, we cycle back to the first bit. In practice,
this should mean that all transitions get their own dedicated lane,
unless we have more pending transitions than lanes, which should
be rare.

We retain our existing behavior of assigning the same lane to all
transitions within the same event. This is achieved by caching the first
lane assigned to a transition, then re-using that one until the next
React task, by which point the event must have finished. This preserves
the guarantee that all transition updates that result from a single
event will be consistent.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tsairinius/react/commits/a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62"},{"sha":"b4658f2daa4990ef8057335cd7202b479bd8d41a","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@gmail.com"},"message":"Reduce some constant duplication (#20761)

Now that interleaved updates are added to a special queue, we no longer
need to shift them into their own lane. We can add to a lane that's
already in the middle of rendering without risk of tearing.

See #20615 for more background.

I've only changed this in the new fork, and only behind the
enableTransitionEntanglements flag.

Most of this commit involves updating tests. The "shift-to-a-new" lane
trick was intentionally used in a handful of tests where two or more
updates need to be scheduled in different lanes. Most of these tests
were written before `startTransition` existed, and all of them were
written before transitions were assigned arbitrary lanes.

So I ported these tests to use `startTransition` instead, which is the
idiomatic way to mark an update as parallel.

I didn't change the old fork at all. Writing these tests in such a way
that they also pass in the old fork actually revealed a few flaws in the

Change-Id: I82c835c572877fedd7ce1a452a83d25819407d9f","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/4f06d670ffab9e6f4f3bca06888ee047f86497e8"},{"sha":"ba45035f3a69de4e0bfe6b5a5705c486940634af","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Fix replay issue in round-robin reads.

Previously we indexed requests by (1) round index and (2) pointer addresses. This is a problem when we get multiple requests for the same round, e.g. due to retries. This could cause the same consumer to be counted multiple times, potentially producing a round of data before all consumers are ready.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 356858844
Change-Id: I2511fabb769bb5211b4d7d9c4185df4f3ce0e4cc","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/ba45035f3a69de4e0bfe6b5a5705c486940634af"},{"sha":"05756fcc81f6b5c2152d597b6285b350e7b05e36","author":{"name":"Doe Hyun Yoon","email":"2bed64b9009034c7d8617d2ea58929f25c2cde7d@google.com"},"message":"Set default device info if device type is neither CPU nor GPU.

OpLevelCostEstimator::GetDeviceInfo() returns GFLOPs/sec and GB/sec of
the assumed machine, but currently it assumes the device type is either CPU
or GPU. We didn't expect other device types would be passed during the Grappler
optimization as transfer operations such as _Send and _Recv are added when
a graph actually runs. In some occasions, we encountered the input graph
includes _HostSend op (it is possible that the graph includes _Send or _Recv
ops; that happened in some test cases).

Device type not CPU / GPU currently causes crash; to avoid such a case, we
assume unknown device type as transfer operations over PCIe; setting
default PCIe x16 gen3 bandwidth to avoid crash.

As the GetDeviceInfo() method is virtual, one may override this method
if more precise device info is needed.

Change-Id: I82c835c572877fedd7ce1a452a83d25819407d9f","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/isanjit3/tensorflow/commits/4f06d670ffab9e6f4f3bca06888ee047f86497e8"},{"sha":"ba45035f3a69de4e0bfe6b5a5705c486940634af","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Fix replay issue in round-robin reads.

Previously we indexed requests by (1) round index and (2) pointer addresses. This is a problem when we get multiple requests for the same round, e.g. due to retries. This could cause the same consumer to be counted multiple times, potentially producing a round of data before all consumers are ready.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 356858844
Change-Id: I2511fabb769bb5211b4d7d9c4185df4f3ce0e4cc","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/isanjit3/tensorflow/commits/ba45035f3a69de4e0bfe6b5a5705c486940634af"},{"sha":"05756fcc81f6b5c2152d597b6285b350e7b05e36","author":{"name":"Doe Hyun Yoon","email":"2bed64b9009034c7d8617d2ea58929f25c2cde7d@google.com"},"message":"Set default device info if device type is neither CPU nor GPU.

OpLevelCostEstimator::GetDeviceInfo() returns GFLOPs/sec and GB/sec of
the assumed machine, but currently it assumes the device type is either CPU
or GPU. We didn't expect other device types would be passed during the Grappler
optimization as transfer operations such as _Send and _Recv are added when
a graph actually runs. In some occasions, we encountered the input graph
includes _HostSend op (it is possible that the graph includes _Send or _Recv
ops; that happened in some test cases).

Device type not CPU / GPU currently causes crash; to avoid such a case, we
assume unknown device type as transfer operations over PCIe; setting
default PCIe x16 gen3 bandwidth to avoid crash.

As the GetDeviceInfo() method is virtual, one may override this method
if more precise device info is needed.

Handle patterns like this:

   %data = type[X,Y] hlo(...)
   %reshape = type[X,1,Y,1] reshape(%data)
   %reshape2 = type[1,X,1,Y,1] reshape(%reshape)
   %ag = type[R,X,1,Y,1] all-gather(%reshape2), dimension={0}
 to:
   %data = type[X,Y] hlo(...)
   %ag = type[R*X,Y] all-gather(%data), dimension={0}
   %reshape = type[R,X,1,Y,1] reshape(%ag)

Although it would be nice to have "take ownership" constructor with a simple pointer argument, it is harder to signal this intention in a type signature.

[{"sha":"696e736be11b22e8d4fa40438d235b63db7fddde","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Warn if static flag is accidentally cleared (#20807)

* Warn if static flag is accidentally cleared

"Static" fiber flags are flags that are meant to exist for the lifetime
of a component. It's really important not to accidentally reset these,
because we use them to decide whether or not to perform some operation
on a tree (which we can do because they get bubbled via `subtreeFlags)`.

We've had several bugs that were caused by this mistake, so we actually
don't rely on static flags anywhere, yet. But we'd like to.

So let's roll out this warning and see if it fires anywhere. Once we
can confirm that there are no warnings, we can assume that it's safe
to start using static flags.

I did not wrap it behind a feature flag, because it's dev-only, and we
can use our internal warning filter to hide this from the console.

* Intentionally clear static flag to test warning

* ...and fix it again","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MichaelDeBoey/react/commits/696e736be11b22e8d4fa40438d235b63db7fddde"}]

[{"sha":"750beea911c7b82b45667d62021cb0bbf22709c8","author":{"name":"Sanjoy Das","email":"d72748a98fd8b476107003df407128e166d060ac@google.com"},"message":"Set the default value for the use_gpu-param to True in test utilities

Also, fix a bug in IsFunctionCallOp found by this CL.

Contrary to what it sounds like, `use_gpu` does not force the test to run on
GPUs, it merely *allows* the test to run on GPUs (there is a separate
`force_gpu` option for forcing).  This means setting `use_gpu` to `True` means
that the test will run on GPUs if one is available.

Given that setting `use_gpu` to `True` by default makes sense, and there should
be a good reason for a test to set it to `False` (which disallows GPU use, even
when one is available).

For this reason, this CL changes the default value of `use_gpu`.  As you can
see, this has already found a few real bugs.

In a later CL I will remove instances that pass use_gpu=True explicitly as those
should no longer be necessary.

While the field in the Go struct is named `NanoCPUs`, it has a JSON label to
use `NanoCpus`, which was added in the original pull request (not clear what
the reason was); 846baf1fd3efcbfbf9d3eb99e436ca9a59d3e185

Some notes:

- Golang processes field names case-insensitive, so when *using* the API,
  both cases should work, but when inspecting a container, the field is
  returned as `NanoCpus`.
- This only affects Containers.Resources. The `Limits` and `Reservation`
  for SwarmKit services and SwarmKit "nodes" do not override the name
  for JSON, so have the canonical (`NanoCPUs`) casing.

[{"sha":"696e736be11b22e8d4fa40438d235b63db7fddde","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Warn if static flag is accidentally cleared (#20807)

* Warn if static flag is accidentally cleared

"Static" fiber flags are flags that are meant to exist for the lifetime
of a component. It's really important not to accidentally reset these,
because we use them to decide whether or not to perform some operation
on a tree (which we can do because they get bubbled via `subtreeFlags)`.

We've had several bugs that were caused by this mistake, so we actually
don't rely on static flags anywhere, yet. But we'd like to.

So let's roll out this warning and see if it fires anywhere. Once we
can confirm that there are no warnings, we can assume that it's safe
to start using static flags.

I did not wrap it behind a feature flag, because it's dev-only, and we
can use our internal warning filter to hide this from the console.

* Intentionally clear static flag to test warning

* ...and fix it again","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Qwerty0x64/react/commits/696e736be11b22e8d4fa40438d235b63db7fddde"}]

Change-Id: Iff329b8f81777f895333726e8ca98e2d3ad4ddb5","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/melG81/tensorflow/commits/443f13e41a34d70dc5dd9509e700ccf79324b5a2"},{"sha":"750beea911c7b82b45667d62021cb0bbf22709c8","author":{"name":"Sanjoy Das","email":"d72748a98fd8b476107003df407128e166d060ac@google.com"},"message":"Set the default value for the use_gpu-param to True in test utilities

Also, fix a bug in IsFunctionCallOp found by this CL.

Contrary to what it sounds like, `use_gpu` does not force the test to run on
GPUs, it merely *allows* the test to run on GPUs (there is a separate
`force_gpu` option for forcing).  This means setting `use_gpu` to `True` means
that the test will run on GPUs if one is available.

Given that setting `use_gpu` to `True` by default makes sense, and there should
be a good reason for a test to set it to `False` (which disallows GPU use, even
when one is available).

For this reason, this CL changes the default value of `use_gpu`.  As you can
see, this has already found a few real bugs.

In a later CL I will remove instances that pass use_gpu=True explicitly as those
should no longer be necessary.

This will allow the unit tests to be run on additional targets that need
some addiitonal initialization (for example cornstone_300 from #46830).

This particular change is broken out from the Cornstone PR #46830 to
be able to have smaller more reviewable PRs.

In the past, we have added state to the DebugLog() and
GetCurrentTimeTicks() functions as a way to avoid having an
InitializeTarget function. With this change, we are deciding to go with
an explicit intitialization step instead.

This change has added calls to tflite::InitializeTarget to the tests,
benchmarks, and examples and converted the Arduino and SparkfunEdge to
make use of this explicit initialization.

The changes for the Arduino and SparkfunEdge have not been tested on
actual hardware.

* feat(kumactl) add kumactl install crds cmd

- Introduced new `kumactl` command: `kumactl install crds`
  which will render all Custom Resource Definitions used by kuma.
  By providing `--only-missing` flag it will output content of
  CRDs which are not present in the cluster (it will use the same
  approach to get kubeconfig as `kumactl install control-plane`
  - I added small script which I will be using in helm hooks
    to generate missing CRDs. I'm doing it via script, and not by
    directly providing `entrypoint` or `cmd` to container, as there
    is logic to check if command `kumactl install crds \
     --only-missing` returns anything as if there are already
    all CRDs present the command `kubectl create -f -` would fail
    and I don't see any other, easier way to handle this case
- Added helm's pre-upgrade hook to install missing crds, which is
  using the container with `kumactl` mentioned above
- Modified helm's `values.yaml` file to reflect changes mentioned
  above

* fix(kumactl) fix sh scripts (removed function key)

Updated .golden files to reflect the new command
`kumactl install crds`

* feat(*) add helm upgrade logic to e2e framework

Introduced to our e2e tests framework functionalities to upgrade
kuma helm charts.

* fix(*) add helm repo for kuma in CI

As we currently are using our external helm repository, to install
some older versions of Kuma during the helm upgrade tests,
we have to configure helm to use this repository first

* feat(kumactl) introuce ctx to install crds command

Currently Tensor does not have a constructor that allows to pass TensorBuffer ownership to Tensor. It can only be done with Ref()/Unref() operations pair.

core::RefCountPtr<TensorBuffer> clearly communicates the ownership of the buffer.

Although it would be nice to have "take ownership" constructor with a simple pointer argument, it is harder to signal this intention in a type signature.

Change-Id: I28966d39de769c7388a0ef300d2006c070b20c14","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/KabirKwatra/tensorflow/commits/d73cfcdbba5473a6468523aeb2b89c84f738a230"},{"sha":"6d7e583c890e852319629ee00bf8ca87c233475b","author":{"name":"Jose Baiocchi","email":"2c5064b37befcda621d52370dff81833faf858cd@google.com"},"message":"Allow locking the profiler via environment variable

Alternative to https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46544

Use case: Allow an outer profiler (e.g., a command-line tool) to set an environment variable to prevent interference from TF Profiler. We already have mutual exclusion of profiler clients via ProfilerLock to guarantee at most one profiler client can actually profile. The environment variable TF_DISABLE_PROFILING, when set to 1, disables all profiler clients. We assume that clients already know how to gracefully handle failure to profile.

The previous changes removing support for using the trailing positional
argument as a working directory missed a spot in the apply/destroy
command implementation. We still support this argument for applying a
saved plan:

    terraform apply foo.tfplan

However, if you pass a positional path which doesn't "look like" a plan
(for example, the path to a configuration directory), Terraform would
silently ignore it and continue.

This commit fixes that by adding an error message if the user specifies
a path which the plan loader rejects as not "looking like" a plan. This
message includes a reference to the `-chdir` flag as a pointer about
what to do next.

We also rearrange the error message when calling `terraform destroy`
with a plan file argument, and add test coverage for the above. While
we're here, update the destroy tests to copy the fixture directory,

Errors encountered when parsing flags for apply, plan, and refresh were
being suppressed. This resulted in a generic usage error when using an
invalid `-target` flag.

This commit makes several changes to address this. First, these commands
now output the flag parse error before exiting, leaving at least some
hint about the error. You can verify this manually with something like:

    terraform apply -invalid-flag

We also change how target attributes are parsed, moving the
responsibility from the flags instance to the command. This allows us to
customize the diagnostic output to be more user friendly. The
diagnostics now look like:

```shellsession
$ terraform apply -no-color -target=foo

Error: Invalid target "foo"

Resource specification must include a resource type and name.
```

Finally, we add test coverage for both parsing of target flags, and at
the command level for successful use of resource targeting. These tests
focus on the UI output (via the change summary and refresh logs), as the
functionality of targeting is covered by the context tests in the
terraform package.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/4991cc48354275f5a190b12e0f8cdafb952fdc0a"},{"sha":"96be094ecdc9e7c1350aac198c64fa4f5776cfe0","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #27711 from hashicorp/alisdair/fix-target-flag-parsing-and-add-tests

[{"sha":"6ba169665b33035f93849d5f5fbfdefa45473e6e","author":{"name":"Eugene Zhulenev","email":"117600c937fb2af1218bd1d47c746d36a58fc7b4@google.com"},"message":"[tensorflow] Add a Tensor constructor that allows to transfer TensorBuffer ownership

Currently Tensor does not have a constructor that allows to pass TensorBuffer ownership to Tensor. It can only be done with Ref()/Unref() operations pair.

core::RefCountPtr<TensorBuffer> clearly communicates the ownership of the buffer.

Although it would be nice to have "take ownership" constructor with a simple pointer argument, it is harder to signal this intention in a type signature.

[{"sha":"05756fcc81f6b5c2152d597b6285b350e7b05e36","author":{"name":"Doe Hyun Yoon","email":"2bed64b9009034c7d8617d2ea58929f25c2cde7d@google.com"},"message":"Set default device info if device type is neither CPU nor GPU.

OpLevelCostEstimator::GetDeviceInfo() returns GFLOPs/sec and GB/sec of
the assumed machine, but currently it assumes the device type is either CPU
or GPU. We didn't expect other device types would be passed during the Grappler
optimization as transfer operations such as _Send and _Recv are added when
a graph actually runs. In some occasions, we encountered the input graph
includes _HostSend op (it is possible that the graph includes _Send or _Recv
ops; that happened in some test cases).

Device type not CPU / GPU currently causes crash; to avoid such a case, we
assume unknown device type as transfer operations over PCIe; setting
default PCIe x16 gen3 bandwidth to avoid crash.

As the GetDeviceInfo() method is virtual, one may override this method
if more precise device info is needed.

Change-Id: Iff329b8f81777f895333726e8ca98e2d3ad4ddb5","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/443f13e41a34d70dc5dd9509e700ccf79324b5a2"},{"sha":"750beea911c7b82b45667d62021cb0bbf22709c8","author":{"name":"Sanjoy Das","email":"d72748a98fd8b476107003df407128e166d060ac@google.com"},"message":"Set the default value for the use_gpu-param to True in test utilities

Also, fix a bug in IsFunctionCallOp found by this CL.

Contrary to what it sounds like, `use_gpu` does not force the test to run on
GPUs, it merely *allows* the test to run on GPUs (there is a separate
`force_gpu` option for forcing).  This means setting `use_gpu` to `True` means
that the test will run on GPUs if one is available.

Given that setting `use_gpu` to `True` by default makes sense, and there should
be a good reason for a test to set it to `False` (which disallows GPU use, even
when one is available).

For this reason, this CL changes the default value of `use_gpu`.  As you can
see, this has already found a few real bugs.

In a later CL I will remove instances that pass use_gpu=True explicitly as those
should no longer be necessary.

This could cause the same consumer to be counted multiple times, potentially producing a round of data before all consumers are ready.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 356858844
Change-Id: I2511fabb769bb5211b4d7d9c4185df4f3ce0e4cc","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/NeatNerdPrime/tensorflow/commits/ba45035f3a69de4e0bfe6b5a5705c486940634af"},{"sha":"05756fcc81f6b5c2152d597b6285b350e7b05e36","author":{"name":"Doe Hyun Yoon","email":"2bed64b9009034c7d8617d2ea58929f25c2cde7d@google.com"},"message":"Set default device info if device type is neither CPU nor GPU.

OpLevelCostEstimator::GetDeviceInfo() returns GFLOPs/sec and GB/sec of
the assumed machine, but currently it assumes the device type is either CPU
or GPU. We didn't expect other device types would be passed during the Grappler
optimization as transfer operations such as _Send and _Recv are added when
a graph actually runs. In some occasions, we encountered the input graph
includes _HostSend op (it is possible that the graph includes _Send or _Recv
ops; that happened in some test cases).

Device type not CPU / GPU currently causes crash; to avoid such a case, we
assume unknown device type as transfer operations over PCIe; setting
default PCIe x16 gen3 bandwidth to avoid crash.

As the GetDeviceInfo() method is virtual, one may override this method
if more precise device info is needed.

While the field in the Go struct is named `NanoCPUs`, it has a JSON label to
use `NanoCpus`, which was added in the original pull request (not clear what
the reason was); 846baf1fd3efcbfbf9d3eb99e436ca9a59d3e185

Some notes:

- Golang processes field names case-insensitive, so when *using* the API,
  both cases should work, but when inspecting a container, the field is
  returned as `NanoCpus`.
- This only affects Containers.Resources. The `Limits` and `Reservation`
  for SwarmKit services and SwarmKit "nodes" do not override the name
  for JSON, so have the canonical (`NanoCPUs`) casing.

cli: Optimize for large multi-line string outputs","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/04e512d2f97e0984e23a8a8f0f8a3f79470c710e"},{"sha":"c5a6aa31d384649d67010ef6eae77a8bf1058f83","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"cli: Add initial command views abstraction

Terraform supports multiple output formats for several sub-commands.
The default format is user-readable text, but many sub-commands support
a `-json` flag to output a machine-readable format for the result. The
output command also supports a `-raw` flag for a simpler, scripting-
focused machine readable format.

This commit adds a "views" abstraction, intended to help ensure
consistency between the various output formats. This extracts the render
specific code from the command package, and moves it into a views
package. Each command is expected to create an interface for its view,
and one or more implementations of that interface.

By doing so, we separate the concerns of generating the sub-command
result from rendering the result in the specified output format. This
should make it easier to ensure that all output formats will be updated
together when changes occur in the result-generating phase.

There are some other consequences of this restructuring:

- Views now directly access the terminal streams, rather than the
  now-redundant cli.Ui instance;
- With the reorganization of commands, parsing CLI arguments is now the
  responsibility of a separate "arguments" package.

For now, views are added only for the output sub-command, as an example.
Because this command uses code which is shared with the apply and
refresh commands, those are also partially updated.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/c5a6aa31d384649d67010ef6eae77a8bf1058f83"},{"sha":"594aa228c0e87b49eb4d399bbf5c2574102bb9c6","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"cli: Add global view arguments parser

Rather than modifying and relying on the existing Meta.process
argument extractor, we can more clearly handle global CLI flags using
a separate parser step. This allows us to explicitly configure the view
in the command.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/594aa228c0e87b49eb4d399bbf5c2574102bb9c6"}]

Alternative to https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46544

Use case: Allow an outer profiler (e.g., a command-line tool) to set an environment variable to prevent interference from TF Profiler. We already have mutual exclusion of profiler clients via ProfilerLock to guarantee at most one profiler client can actually profile. The environment variable TF_DISABLE_PROFILING, when set to 1, disables all profiler clients. We assume that clients already know how to gracefully handle failure to profile.

[{"sha":"696e736be11b22e8d4fa40438d235b63db7fddde","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Warn if static flag is accidentally cleared (#20807)

* Warn if static flag is accidentally cleared

"Static" fiber flags are flags that are meant to exist for the lifetime
of a component. It's really important not to accidentally reset these,
because we use them to decide whether or not to perform some operation
on a tree (which we can do because they get bubbled via `subtreeFlags)`.

We've had several bugs that were caused by this mistake, so we actually
don't rely on static flags anywhere, yet. But we'd like to.

So let's roll out this warning and see if it fires anywhere. Once we
can confirm that there are no warnings, we can assume that it's safe
to start using static flags.

I did not wrap it behind a feature flag, because it's dev-only, and we
can use our internal warning filter to hide this from the console.

* Intentionally clear static flag to test warning

* ...and fix it again","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rafsanulhasan/react/commits/696e736be11b22e8d4fa40438d235b63db7fddde"}]

[{"sha":"a22f61c327293625cf6e753a35673b969beaaacb","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Remove isEqual argument

The isEqual argument mostly meant as a strawman. It has some known
flaws: chiefly, if the isEqual function must always be in sync with the
selector function; if isEqual changes, then isEqual is not valid for
that render, because it'd be comparing the previous type with a
new type.

We have a few other ideas for how to solve the underlying problem, but
in the meantime, let's remove it since we know it's not what we'll end
up shipping.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/a22f61c327293625cf6e753a35673b969beaaacb"}]

PiperOrigin-RevId: 356904310
Change-Id: Iff329b8f81777f895333726e8ca98e2d3ad4ddb5","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/advaitjain/tensorflow/commits/443f13e41a34d70dc5dd9509e700ccf79324b5a2"},{"sha":"750beea911c7b82b45667d62021cb0bbf22709c8","author":{"name":"Sanjoy Das","email":"d72748a98fd8b476107003df407128e166d060ac@google.com"},"message":"Set the default value for the use_gpu-param to True in test utilities

Also, fix a bug in IsFunctionCallOp found by this CL.

Contrary to what it sounds like, `use_gpu` does not force the test to run on
GPUs, it merely *allows* the test to run on GPUs (there is a separate
`force_gpu` option for forcing).  This means setting `use_gpu` to `True` means
that the test will run on GPUs if one is available.

Given that setting `use_gpu` to `True` by default makes sense, and there should
be a good reason for a test to set it to `False` (which disallows GPU use, even
when one is available).

For this reason, this CL changes the default value of `use_gpu`.  As you can
see, this has already found a few real bugs.

In a later CL I will remove instances that pass use_gpu=True explicitly as those
should no longer be necessary.

Currently Tensor does not have a constructor that allows to pass TensorBuffer ownership to Tensor. It can only be done with Ref()/Unref() operations pair.

core::RefCountPtr<TensorBuffer> clearly communicates the ownership of the buffer.

Although it would be nice to have "take ownership" constructor with a simple pointer argument, it is harder to signal this intention in a type signature.

Change-Id: I28966d39de769c7388a0ef300d2006c070b20c14","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/d73cfcdbba5473a6468523aeb2b89c84f738a230"},{"sha":"6d7e583c890e852319629ee00bf8ca87c233475b","author":{"name":"Jose Baiocchi","email":"2c5064b37befcda621d52370dff81833faf858cd@google.com"},"message":"Allow locking the profiler via environment variable

Alternative to https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46544

Use case: Allow an outer profiler (e.g., a command-line tool) to set an environment variable to prevent interference from TF Profiler. We already have mutual exclusion of profiler clients via ProfilerLock to guarantee at most one profiler client can actually profile. The environment variable TF_DISABLE_PROFILING, when set to 1, disables all profiler clients. We assume that clients already know how to gracefully handle failure to profile.

Previously we indexed requests by (1) round index and (2) pointer addresses. This is a problem when we get multiple requests for the same round, e.g. due to retries. This could cause the same consumer to be counted multiple times, potentially producing a round of data before all consumers are ready.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 356858844
Change-Id: I2511fabb769bb5211b4d7d9c4185df4f3ce0e4cc","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/osmaelo/tensorflow/commits/ba45035f3a69de4e0bfe6b5a5705c486940634af"},{"sha":"05756fcc81f6b5c2152d597b6285b350e7b05e36","author":{"name":"Doe Hyun Yoon","email":"2bed64b9009034c7d8617d2ea58929f25c2cde7d@google.com"},"message":"Set default device info if device type is neither CPU nor GPU.

OpLevelCostEstimator::GetDeviceInfo() returns GFLOPs/sec and GB/sec of
the assumed machine, but currently it assumes the device type is either CPU
or GPU. We didn't expect other device types would be passed during the Grappler
optimization as transfer operations such as _Send and _Recv are added when
a graph actually runs. In some occasions, we encountered the input graph
includes _HostSend op (it is possible that the graph includes _Send or _Recv
ops; that happened in some test cases).

Device type not CPU / GPU currently causes crash; to avoid such a case, we
assume unknown device type as transfer operations over PCIe; setting
default PCIe x16 gen3 bandwidth to avoid crash.

As the GetDeviceInfo() method is virtual, one may override this method
if more precise device info is needed.

[{"sha":"750beea911c7b82b45667d62021cb0bbf22709c8","author":{"name":"Sanjoy Das","email":"d72748a98fd8b476107003df407128e166d060ac@google.com"},"message":"Set the default value for the use_gpu-param to True in test utilities

Also, fix a bug in IsFunctionCallOp found by this CL.

Contrary to what it sounds like, `use_gpu` does not force the test to run on
GPUs, it merely *allows* the test to run on GPUs (there is a separate
`force_gpu` option for forcing).  This means setting `use_gpu` to `True` means
that the test will run on GPUs if one is available.

Given that setting `use_gpu` to `True` by default makes sense, and there should
be a good reason for a test to set it to `False` (which disallows GPU use, even
when one is available).

For this reason, this CL changes the default value of `use_gpu`.  As you can
see, this has already found a few real bugs.

In a later CL I will remove instances that pass use_gpu=True explicitly as those
should no longer be necessary.

Although it would be nice to have "take ownership" constructor with a simple pointer argument, it is harder to signal this intention in a type signature.

Change-Id: I28966d39de769c7388a0ef300d2006c070b20c14","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/d73cfcdbba5473a6468523aeb2b89c84f738a230"},{"sha":"6d7e583c890e852319629ee00bf8ca87c233475b","author":{"name":"Jose Baiocchi","email":"2c5064b37befcda621d52370dff81833faf858cd@google.com"},"message":"Allow locking the profiler via environment variable

Alternative to https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46544

Use case: Allow an outer profiler (e.g., a command-line tool) to set an environment variable to prevent interference from TF Profiler. We already have mutual exclusion of profiler clients via ProfilerLock to guarantee at most one profiler client can actually profile. The environment variable TF_DISABLE_PROFILING, when set to 1, disables all profiler clients. We assume that clients already know how to gracefully handle failure to profile.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 356904310
Change-Id: Iff329b8f81777f895333726e8ca98e2d3ad4ddb5","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/443f13e41a34d70dc5dd9509e700ccf79324b5a2"},{"sha":"750beea911c7b82b45667d62021cb0bbf22709c8","author":{"name":"Sanjoy Das","email":"d72748a98fd8b476107003df407128e166d060ac@google.com"},"message":"Set the default value for the use_gpu-param to True in test utilities

Also, fix a bug in IsFunctionCallOp found by this CL.

Contrary to what it sounds like, `use_gpu` does not force the test to run on
GPUs, it merely *allows* the test to run on GPUs (there is a separate
`force_gpu` option for forcing).  This means setting `use_gpu` to `True` means
that the test will run on GPUs if one is available.

Given that setting `use_gpu` to `True` by default makes sense, and there should
be a good reason for a test to set it to `False` (which disallows GPU use, even
when one is available).

For this reason, this CL changes the default value of `use_gpu`.  As you can
see, this has already found a few real bugs.

In a later CL I will remove instances that pass use_gpu=True explicitly as those
should no longer be necessary.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 356904310
Change-Id: Iff329b8f81777f895333726e8ca98e2d3ad4ddb5","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/443f13e41a34d70dc5dd9509e700ccf79324b5a2"},{"sha":"750beea911c7b82b45667d62021cb0bbf22709c8","author":{"name":"Sanjoy Das","email":"d72748a98fd8b476107003df407128e166d060ac@google.com"},"message":"Set the default value for the use_gpu-param to True in test utilities

Also, fix a bug in IsFunctionCallOp found by this CL.

Contrary to what it sounds like, `use_gpu` does not force the test to run on
GPUs, it merely *allows* the test to run on GPUs (there is a separate
`force_gpu` option for forcing).  This means setting `use_gpu` to `True` means
that the test will run on GPUs if one is available.

Given that setting `use_gpu` to `True` by default makes sense, and there should
be a good reason for a test to set it to `False` (which disallows GPU use, even
when one is available).

For this reason, this CL changes the default value of `use_gpu`.  As you can
see, this has already found a few real bugs.

In a later CL I will remove instances that pass use_gpu=True explicitly as those
should no longer be necessary.

This could cause the same consumer to be counted multiple times, potentially producing a round of data before all consumers are ready.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 356858844
Change-Id: I2511fabb769bb5211b4d7d9c4185df4f3ce0e4cc","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Cache-Cloud/tensorflow/commits/ba45035f3a69de4e0bfe6b5a5705c486940634af"},{"sha":"05756fcc81f6b5c2152d597b6285b350e7b05e36","author":{"name":"Doe Hyun Yoon","email":"2bed64b9009034c7d8617d2ea58929f25c2cde7d@google.com"},"message":"Set default device info if device type is neither CPU nor GPU.

OpLevelCostEstimator::GetDeviceInfo() returns GFLOPs/sec and GB/sec of
the assumed machine, but currently it assumes the device type is either CPU
or GPU. We didn't expect other device types would be passed during the Grappler
optimization as transfer operations such as _Send and _Recv are added when
a graph actually runs. In some occasions, we encountered the input graph
includes _HostSend op (it is possible that the graph includes _Send or _Recv
ops; that happened in some test cases).

Device type not CPU / GPU currently causes crash; to avoid such a case, we
assume unknown device type as transfer operations over PCIe; setting
default PCIe x16 gen3 bandwidth to avoid crash.

As the GetDeviceInfo() method is virtual, one may override this method
if more precise device info is needed.

Change-Id: I34e82bca406481aecc42d3240728362ab99b3a01","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/tensorflow/commits/2287f80894c39dde3520659033e58cc7b7406d00"},{"sha":"6ba169665b33035f93849d5f5fbfdefa45473e6e","author":{"name":"Eugene Zhulenev","email":"117600c937fb2af1218bd1d47c746d36a58fc7b4@google.com"},"message":"[tensorflow] Add a Tensor constructor that allows to transfer TensorBuffer ownership

Currently Tensor does not have a constructor that allows to pass TensorBuffer ownership to Tensor. It can only be done with Ref()/Unref() operations pair.

core::RefCountPtr<TensorBuffer> clearly communicates the ownership of the buffer.

Although it would be nice to have "take ownership" constructor with a simple pointer argument, it is harder to signal this intention in a type signature.

Change-Id: I28966d39de769c7388a0ef300d2006c070b20c14","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/tensorflow/commits/d73cfcdbba5473a6468523aeb2b89c84f738a230"},{"sha":"6d7e583c890e852319629ee00bf8ca87c233475b","author":{"name":"Jose Baiocchi","email":"2c5064b37befcda621d52370dff81833faf858cd@google.com"},"message":"Allow locking the profiler via environment variable

Alternative to https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46544

Use case: Allow an outer profiler (e.g., a command-line tool) to set an environment variable to prevent interference from TF Profiler. We already have mutual exclusion of profiler clients via ProfilerLock to guarantee at most one profiler client can actually profile. The environment variable TF_DISABLE_PROFILING, when set to 1, disables all profiler clients. We assume that clients already know how to gracefully handle failure to profile.

Change-Id: I28966d39de769c7388a0ef300d2006c070b20c14","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/akram/tensorflow/commits/d73cfcdbba5473a6468523aeb2b89c84f738a230"},{"sha":"6d7e583c890e852319629ee00bf8ca87c233475b","author":{"name":"Jose Baiocchi","email":"2c5064b37befcda621d52370dff81833faf858cd@google.com"},"message":"Allow locking the profiler via environment variable

Alternative to https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46544

Use case: Allow an outer profiler (e.g., a command-line tool) to set an environment variable to prevent interference from TF Profiler. We already have mutual exclusion of profiler clients via ProfilerLock to guarantee at most one profiler client can actually profile. The environment variable TF_DISABLE_PROFILING, when set to 1, disables all profiler clients. We assume that clients already know how to gracefully handle failure to profile.

[{"sha":"696e736be11b22e8d4fa40438d235b63db7fddde","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Warn if static flag is accidentally cleared (#20807)

* Warn if static flag is accidentally cleared

"Static" fiber flags are flags that are meant to exist for the lifetime
of a component. It's really important not to accidentally reset these,
because we use them to decide whether or not to perform some operation
on a tree (which we can do because they get bubbled via `subtreeFlags)`.

We've had several bugs that were caused by this mistake, so we actually
don't rely on static flags anywhere, yet. But we'd like to.

So let's roll out this warning and see if it fires anywhere. Once we
can confirm that there are no warnings, we can assume that it's safe
to start using static flags.

I did not wrap it behind a feature flag, because it's dev-only, and we
can use our internal warning filter to hide this from the console.

* Intentionally clear static flag to test warning

* ...and fix it again","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/facebook/react/commits/696e736be11b22e8d4fa40438d235b63db7fddde"}]

  for JSON, so have the canonical (`NanoCPUs`) casing.

`320=2^6*5` and `480=2^5*3*5`, so the improved radix3 version is used.

[{"sha":"916537f56ada9b351ec4efcd054d6b77edd6d6ce","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Extend AllGather CSE to look through reshapes that add degenerate dims.

Handle patterns like this:

   %data = type[X,Y] hlo(...)
   %reshape = type[X,1,Y,1] reshape(%data)
   %reshape2 = type[1,X,1,Y,1] reshape(%reshape)
   %ag = type[R,X,1,Y,1] all-gather(%reshape2), dimension={0}
 to:
   %data = type[X,Y] hlo(...)
   %ag = type[R*X,Y] all-gather(%data), dimension={0}
   %reshape = type[R,X,1,Y,1] reshape(%ag)

[{"sha":"05756fcc81f6b5c2152d597b6285b350e7b05e36","author":{"name":"Doe Hyun Yoon","email":"2bed64b9009034c7d8617d2ea58929f25c2cde7d@google.com"},"message":"Set default device info if device type is neither CPU nor GPU.

OpLevelCostEstimator::GetDeviceInfo() returns GFLOPs/sec and GB/sec of
the assumed machine, but currently it assumes the device type is either CPU
or GPU. We didn't expect other device types would be passed during the Grappler
optimization as transfer operations such as _Send and _Recv are added when
a graph actually runs. In some occasions, we encountered the input graph
includes _HostSend op (it is possible that the graph includes _Send or _Recv
ops; that happened in some test cases).

Device type not CPU / GPU currently causes crash; to avoid such a case, we
assume unknown device type as transfer operations over PCIe; setting
default PCIe x16 gen3 bandwidth to avoid crash.

As the GetDeviceInfo() method is virtual, one may override this method
if more precise device info is needed.
